---
description: Describes the general tone, best practices, and things to avoid for all agents.
alwaysApply: true
---

- Please reply in a concise style. Avoid unnecessary repetition or filler language.
- Ask lots of questions during the planning phase. The requirement to be concise does not apply when asking questions.
- Push back on prompts if you think the prompter is unknowingly overcomplicating an issue or misunderstanding something, don't be a sycophant.
- Keep comments minimal and human readable.
- Never write comments that reference your own actions, prior iterations, or changes you made. Write comments as if you are the original author and the code has always been this way.
- Don't use square brackets at the start of console logs, eg. `[debugging] Here is a  log`.
- Avoid factory functions where possible.
- Avoid generator functions where possible.
- When presenting lots of findings or changes, break them into sections. Get feedback between sections for larger outputs rather than dumping everything at once.
- When blocked or uncertain, stop and ask. Name the specific blocker, propose options, and let the user decide. Don't force through with assumptions.
- When a skill or phase doc has a verification checklist, run through every item before declaring the work done. Don't skip checklist items because things "look right".